etymologies: mid 19th century; earliest use found in Francis Morgan Nichols (1826–1915). From Anglo-Norman maynpast, meynpast, Old French mainpast household from post-classical Latin manupastus household, member of a household from classical Latin manū, ablative singular of manus hand + pāstus, past participle of pāscere to feed

definitions: A person's household, or a member of it; a domestic; a dependant.
